Included in this homework is the same bobcat occupancy modeling dataset from homework 5: Bobcat.csv: detection / non-detection of bobcat at each camera. Each row is a camera, and each column is a replicate survey (1 day). p covariates.csv: number of people (divided by 100) photographed. Each row is a camera, and each column is a replicate survey (1 day). This is a detection covariate. psi covariates.csv: the single covariate represents the proportion of area within 5km recently disturbed (e.g., logging, housing development). Treat this as a site-level covariate.

  1. Perform model selection with AIC. What is your top model? How do you know? Is there model selection uncertainty?

The top model is detection: intercept-only and occupancy: disturbance. We know because it is listed first and has a delta AIC = 0. However, the model that includes detection:people and occupancy:disturbance has a delta AIC < 2, so it also offers substantial empirical support for the top model. Because of this, there is model selection uncertainty.

library(AICcmodavg)
cand.list <- list(
  IxI = fit1,
  PxI = fit2,
  IxD = fit3,
  PxD = fit4
)
  
models <- aictab(cand.set = cand.list, second.ord = F)
head(models)
